Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In order to enable export of animals or their products from
countries which are not FMD-free without vaccination, the OIE (World
Organisation for Animal Health) has developed a system by which such
countries can declare that they maintain a zone, within their
boundaries, which is FMD-free without vaccination. Exports from such
zones are subsequently allowed to FMD-free countries.

According to article 2.2.10.4 of OIE's Terrestrial Animal Health Code
(<http://www.oie.int/eng/normes/mcode/en_chapitre_2.2.10.htm>), an
FMD free zone where vaccination is not practised can be established
in either an FMD free country where vaccination is practised or in a
country of which parts are infected. Susceptible animals in the FMD
free zone should be separated by a buffer zone or by
physical/geographical barriers from the rest of the country and from
neighboring countries if they are of a different animal health
status, and animal health measures that effectively prevent the entry
of the virus should be implemented.

At present, 9 member-countries are officially recognized as "having
an FMD free zone where vaccination is not practised, according to the
provisions of Chapter 2.2.10 of the Terrestrial Code." Namibia is one
of these countries; the FMD-free zone was "designated by the Delegate
of Namibia in a document addressed to the Director General in
February 1997." Namibia's neighbors, Botswana and South Africa, have
a similar status.

On 4 Aug 2008, Namibia notified an outbreak of FMD to the OIE. The
outbreak affected cattle in an area close to a national park where
there are African Buffaloes. A follow-up report was submitted on 17
Aug 2008, addressing 2 additional outbreaks in Kavango, providing
information on the vaccine used (trivalent -- SAT1, SAT2, SAT3). No
serotyping of the involved virus is mentioned. For further details,
including epidemiological data and map, see
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=7274>.
- Mod.AS]
